Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
Among the collection of memory-manipulating functions, the most common is easily memset()

===============================================================================================
COMPILE :

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg288_set_byte$ make
gcc -Wall -g -o pg288_set_byte pg288_set_byte.c;

===============================================================================================
Execution:

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg288_set_byte$ ./pg288_set_byte 

 SUCCESSFULLY SET  THE MEM 
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg288_set_byte$

===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
    A call to memset( ) sets the n bytes starting at s to the byte c and returns s . A frequent
    use is zeroing a block of memory.





